summary:
An extensive class based archive of female body textures.
Add more character to your character with B.I Phenotypes.
descriptionHtml:
Description:
You, are Dragonborn. Touched by the gods, you carry the blood of Akatosh\' childeren in your vains and wield their power against all who would oppose you.

You are the Listener, the Harbinger and the thane of many holds.

You have slain mighty monsters, brought peace to the lands of skyrim and pierced the veil twixt life and death.

And for all your trials and tribulations.......you haven\'t but a single sctratch to show for your efforts.

B.I (or Body Imperfect) Phenotypes is a female body texture replacer mod, with the overall goal of providing gritty, realistic textures for the female protaganists of skyrim.
Although I would like to expand upon the idea of \"Class Specific\" body texures, for the time being the \"Phenotypes\" reference is more of a place holder than anything, to help me, and you keep track of all the various texture sets, of which there are many.

The decision to incorporate phenotypes into this mod was made shortly after beginning this 
project, which was originally intended as a massive overhall of my other mod \"Body Imperfect\" But, as the project grew it became to large to upload as a single or body selective file. So rather than restructure my exsisting mod I opted for a fresh start and a new mod entirley.

This mod is broken up into several sets or \"Phenotypes\", each on refering to one of the four common player classes found in most RPGs, like the \"Mage\" (or mystic, priest, healer, wizard take your pick)  the \"Blade Master\" (warrior, assassin, rogue) the \"Barbarian\" (berzerker, slayer, heavy knight) and the \"Archer\".

Each texture set has been desighed to reflect the nuances of it\'s perspective phenotype, replete with the wounds and scars one would expect from either a hammer wielding barbarian or a fire blazing sorceress, ect.

These textures were also desighned with grit and realism in mind, and I\'ve gone to great lengths in an attempt to create truly unique textures you won\'t find anywhere else.

I hope you enjoy my work and I thank you for your support.



Installation:
At first glance the file structure seems a bit over whelming, but it\'s simpler than it looks so I\'ll
keep this short and sweet.
This mod contains four phenotypes and one base texture set with three versions, one for each body that this mod supports, each Phenotype (archer, barbarian, blade master, sorceress) and their percpective download contain several sub-folders contained within
the main \"data\" folder.
 
Inside the \"Standard Textures\" folder you will find all the baisc textures for the head, hand and body, before you do anything else, copy and paste these files to your skyrim data directory along the following folder path (textures, actors, character, female).

After you have installed those, go back to your phenotype download and open the \"Optional files\" folder.
Inside this folder you will find the various options available for each texture set.
Once you\'ve perused your options copy and paste the file within to the same location as you did the \"Standard Textures\" and overwrite when asked, or if your happy with the \"Standard texture\" set, just ignore the optional files entirley.

Now, that takes care of the \"Phenotypes\" so we will move on to the \"Base Textures\".
The \"Base\" textures sets are arranged differently because the contain options that are not available for the phenotype sets.
First, choose from either the \"plain - hairy\" or \"tanlines - hairy\" folder and copy and paste the contents to the appropriate folder within your skyrim data directory (textures, actors, character, female),  Choose a shaved option from the folders, either \"plain\" (without tanlines) or tanlines and copy/paste the file to the same directory as before, overwrite when asked. (again, the optional files are not required, duh. They are only necassary if you are not happy with the standard \"hairy\" texture\")

Lastly, if choose the sweat texture option simply repeat the previous step, and enjoy.





Optional Files:

Grainy specular Maps:
These specular maps are were made employing a grain filter and Variable de-sat channels to add the look of sweat or pores. Unfortunetly, though this does (in my opion) add more detail to the model it also leaves imperfect seams.

Seamless Specular Maps:
The title says it all, these specular maps are completley seamless, but they are also without any detail at all. These files are those of you who found the seams in original textures less all of the \"Light\" detail from the surface of the body, giving it a slightly cleaner more uniform look.

Resource Files:
As a courtesey to fellow modders I have included Three \"Resource\" files, one for each body
(CBBE, UNP, ADEC) in the form of \"PSD\" files. 
I have incuded these files for those who wish to either edit or expand upon the work I\'ve already done. They are completley \"Open Source\" and can be used by anyone.

ini Configuration files:
Some people have requested my system configuration, so I\'ve included the full \"SkyrimPrefs\" file a an optional download.
////WARNING//// these settings are not intended for low-end computers furthermore, these settings were desighned for \"Third-person\" players, to be used in conjunction with ENB\'s employing \"DOF\", \"Ambient Occlusion\" and  \"SMAA\".


FAQ:
Q: It would look a little strange if all the characters in the game had the exact same scars as     
      me, how do I fix that? 
A: Yes, In order to make your character completely unique you would need to install a custom 
      race, or character specific path mod. I have included links to several of these mods in the 
      \"Recommended Mods\" section.

Q: Are these textures interchangable?
A: The head and hand textures are interchangable with the various body sets, you just have
      to remember to copy and paste all three head/hand textures of what ever set you choose.

Q: Why doesn\'t my character look like the ones in your screenshots?
A: With a game as technically nuanced and easily manipulated as Skyrim, there are many
      factors that effect how something as complicated as a high resolution skin texture might 
      look in-game.
      Anybody who has poked around the nexus on a regular basis has probably noticed the 
      Recent (relativley speaking) popularity of the ENB series over the last several months.
      ENB\'s are by far the quickest and easiest way to drastically modify the look of your game.
      Many ENB\'s, especially higher end, system intensive ENB\'s employ specific features wich 
      wich would alter the look of something like a skin texure. 
      For example, ENB\'s employing Specular mutiplyers will add a glossy sheen to skin and will 
      also exagerate smaller details in the normal map and ENB\'s wich employ large bloom, or 
      HDR lighting effects will diffuse the skin texures, often covering small seam inperfections
      in the process (a pleasant, but completley unintended side effect).
      This is not to say that these textures will look worse with other ENB configurations (they 
      won\'t) but, they may not look the same either. 
      If you want to know what ENB I use download the \"ini configuration settings\" in the 
      optional files section.
      
        

Bugs/Issues:
None that I have found, but I can only do so much testing. Please report any bugs you may find. I can\'t fix them if I don\'t know about them.
